Study Information 
Hypotheses 
H* (focal hypothesis): There will be differences in utilitarian responses to moral conflicts that 
involve non-physical and non-lethal harm between individuals under mortality salience and a 
control group, such that individuals under mortality salience will have lower rates of utilitarian 
responding compared to a control group. 
 
Original finding (written by COS): Individuals under mortality salience (I.e. who have been 
prompted to consider their own death, compared to a control group who considered 
experiencing pain) are less likely to give utilitarian responses to non-lethal moral conflicts (e.g. 
avoiding detection by blocking a crying baby’s mouth, thus restricting oxygen and harming the 
infant), but this manipulation had no comparable effect on control scenarios where in the 
utilitarian response does not conflict with an intuitive response (quieting the baby with a 
pacifier).  
 
Expected pattern of results:  
Individuals under mortality salience will have lower rates of utilitarian responding compared to 
a control group when evaluating moral conflicts in which an individual is victim to non-physical 
and non-lethal harm to the benefit of many others. The original paper found that rates of 
utilitarian responding were lower when individuals were under mortality salience compared to 
a control group when evaluating a non-lethal moral conflict. However, importantly, these 
scenarios brought physical harm to a victim rather than other types of harm (e.g., emotional). In 
cases where there is non-physical and non-lethal harm done to a victim for the benefit of many, 
rates of utilitarian responding should again be lower for individuals under mortality salience 
compared to a control group.  
 
Design Plan 
Study type 

Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or 
lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized 
controlled trials. 
Blinding 
For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they 
have been assigned. 
Is there any additional blinding in this study? 
Participants will be kept blind to the manipulations. Both manipulations will be generated via 
Qualtrics such that participants will only be shown 1 of 2 salience manipulations, and will then 
read both scenarios for the  scenario outcome manipulations, which will be counterbalanced. 
Study design 
Participants will be randomly assigned to 1 of 2 Salience Manipulation conditions (Salience 
manipulation: mortality salience, pain salience) and then read 2 different scenarios that 
correspond to the Scenario Outcome IV (Scenario outcome: conflict, no conflict). Thus, we will 
employ a mixed design in which Salience Manipulation is between-subjects and Scenario 
Outcome is within-subjects (and counterbalanced). To manipulate what is salient, participants 
will be asked to write down and describe emotions associated with  their own death (mortality 
salience condition) or with a painful event (pain salience condition). To manipulate the scenario 
outcome, participants will read about an actor who creates a conflict to help the majority of 
people (conflict condition) or who does not create a conflict to help the majority of people (no 
conflict condition). 
No files selected 
Randomization 
All participants will be randomly assigned to 1 of 2 salience manipulation conditions. 
Randomization will occur after participants who select into the study 1) consent to participate in 
the study, and 2) complete a simple attention check. 
Sampling Plan 
Existing Data 
Registration prior to creation of data 
Explanation of existing data 
This project is being preregistered prior to any new data collection. 
Data collection procedures 
I will recruit healthy 18+ participants from Amazon Mechanical Turk. Within my survey, I will 
require participants to pass one attention check before proceeding into the survey. All 
participants will be paid at a rate of $.20/minute. 
No files selected 
Sample size 

The target analytic sample size is 129. 
Sample size rationale 
Power calculations were done in accordance with the guidelines of the Social Sciences 
Replication Project (SSRP). However, instead of carrying out two rounds of data collection to 
achieve the stage 1 sample size target followed by the stage 2 sample size target as in Phase 1 
of SCORE, in Phase 2 only one data collection effort will be carried out to achieve a single target 
analytic sample size. 
 
The power analysis was based off of the original effect size, for which we are attempting to 
generalize with new scenarios.  
 
Stopping rule 
The planned sample size is 129. After achieving this sample, sampling will stop and planned 
analyses will be run. 
 
In order to achieve the necessary sample size, once the planned sample size is recruited, the 
data will be checked for exclusions and exact additional participants will be recruited. This 
process will continue until the target sample size is met. No hypothesis testing will be 
conducted until the target analytic sample is met.  
 
Variables 
Manipulated variables 
Salience manipulation: mortality salience, pain salience 
--->Mortality salience text: Please briefly describe the emotions that the thought of your own 
death arouses in you. Jot down, as specifically as you can, what you think will happen to you 
physically as you die and once you are physically dead.  
--->Pain salience text: Please briefly describe the emotions that the thought of extreme pain 
arouses in you. Jot down, as specifically as you can, what you think will happen to you physically 
when you experience extreme pain. 
 
Scenario outcome: conflict, no conflict 
--->In the scenario, the outcome will vary with a conflict or no conflict. Below is the text from the 
scenario that will be used 
---> Conflict outcome: “...Janet decides to volunteer to build houses instead of spending the time 
cheering up her mother. She reasons that by volunteering she has the chance to bring about 
more happiness for more people, and this is more important than any duties she has to her 
mother.” 

---> No conflict outcome: “...Janet decides to volunteer to build houses, and then spend time 
with her mother.” 
 
No files selected 
Measured variables 
The primary variable that will be measured is the response to the outcome. Specifically, 
whether or not participants think that the outcome is morally acceptable.  
 
Moral acceptability [what appears first in brackets is in the Conflict condition / No conflict 
condition]: Is it morally acceptable for Janet to spend her time building houses [to help more 
people at the expense of helping her mother / and helping her mother]? The response options 
participants will see will be yes/no. 
No files selected 
